{"meta": {"centerNodeId": "taxonomy-species-foulehaio-carunculatus", "centerNodeType": "taxonomy", "generatedAt": "2026-05-28T16:28:22", "includedNodeCount": 3, "includedLinkCount": 2, "layoutMode": "precomputed-static"}, "center": {"id": "taxonomy-species-foulehaio-carunculatus", "name": "Polynesian wattled honeyeater", "type": "taxonomy"}, "nodes": [{"id": "taxonomy-species-foulehaio-carunculatus", "name": "Polynesian wattled honeyeater", "latinName": "Foulehaio carunculatus", "type": "taxonomy", "taxonomyLevel": "species", "summary": "Polynesian wattled honeyeater（Foulehaio carunculatus）是图谱中的分类级分类节点，当前关联1种鸟类，如Polynesian wattled honeyeater。", "expandable": true, "memberCount": 1, "x": 156.74, "y": -117.51, "z": -614.01}, {"id": "taxonomy-genus-foulehaio", "name": "Foulehaio", "latinName": "Foulehaio", "type": "taxonomy", "taxonomyLevel": "genus", "summary": "Foulehaio（Foulehaio）是图谱中的分类级分类节点，当前关联3种鸟类，如Kikau、Polynesian wattled honeyeater、Fiji wattled honeyeater。", "expandable": true, "memberCount": 3, "x": -463.55, "y": 431.38, "z": 33.25}, {"id": "bird-polynesian-wattled-honeyeater-a1fb87d9", "name": "Polynesian wattled honeyeater", "englishName": "Polynesian wattled honeyeater", "latinName": "Foulehaio carunculatus", "type": "bird", "status": "LC", "summary": "The Polynesian wattled honeyeater (Foulehaio carunculatus) or the eastern wattled honeyeater, is a species of bird in the honeyeater family Meliphagidae. It was considered conspecific with the Fiji wattled honeyeater and the kikau. The species is endemic to the islands of the Central Pacific, occurring on American Samoa, Fiji, Samoa, Tonga, and Wallis and Futuna Islands. Its natural habitats are tropical moist lowland forests, tropical mangrove forests, and tropical moist montane forest. Taxonomy The Polynesian wattled honeyeater was formally described in 1788 by the German naturalist Johann Friedrich Gmelin in his revised and expanded edition of Carl Linnaeus's Systema Naturae. He placed it with the treecreepers in the genus Certhia and coined the binomial name Certhia carunculata. The specific epithet is from Latin caruncula meaning \"a small piece of flesh\" and hence wattled. Gmelin based his description on the \"wattled creeper\" that had been described in 1782 by the English ornithologist John Latham in his book A General Synopsis of Birds. Latham had examined a specimen from Tonga in the collection of the Leverian Museum in London. The Polynesian wattled honeyeater is now one of three honeyeaters placed in the genus Foulehaio that was introduced in 1852 by the German naturalist Ludwig Reichenbach. The species is monotypic: no subspecies are recognised. The Polynesian wattled honeyeater was formerly considered to be conspecific with the Fiji wattled honeyeater (Foulehaio taviunensis) and the kikau (Foulehaio procerior). The species were split based on the results of molecular phylogenetic study published in 2014. References", "shortSummary": "The Polynesian wattled honeyeater (Foulehaio carunculatus) or the eastern wattled honeyeater, is a species of bird in the honeyeater family…", "imageUrl": "https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/df/Wattled_Honeyeater_%28Foulehaio_carunculata%29.jpg/960px-Wattled_Honeyeater_%28Foulehaio_carunculata%29.jpg", "kingdomId": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylumId": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "classId": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genusId": "taxonomy-genus-foulehaio", "speciesId": "taxonomy-species-foulehaio-carunculatus", "taxonomyIds": {"kingdom": "taxonomy-kingdom-animalia", "phylum": "taxonomy-phylum-chordata", "class": "taxonomy-class-aves", "genus": "taxonomy-genus-foulehaio", "species": "taxonomy-species-foulehaio-carunculatus"}, "expandable": true, "x": 156.74, "y": -117.51, "z": -611.54}], "links": [{"key": "bird-polynesian-wattled-honeyeater-a1fb87d9__belongs_to_species__taxonomy-species-foulehaio-carunculatus", "source": "bird-polynesian-wattled-honeyeater-a1fb87d9", "target": "taxonomy-species-foulehaio-car